    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Great Meadows National Wildlife Refuge]]></title>
    <link href="http://dinhyen.github.io/blog/2011/06/22/great-meadows-national-wildlife-refuge/"/>
    <updated>2011-06-22T00:00:00-04:00</updated>
    <id>http://dinhyen.github.io/blog/2011/06/22/great-meadows-national-wildlife-refuge</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>File this as another in the category of &ldquo;places I&rsquo;ve gone by hundreds of times while being clueless that it exists&rdquo;.  This is just steps away from historic Concord Center, which is popular with tourists and cyclists alike.  The Old North Bridge, site of the confrontation that led to &ldquo;the shot heard around the world&rdquo;, is about 5 minutes away, while Thoreau&rsquo;s Walden Pond is just down the road.  On a nice day, you&rsquo;d see a constant train of cyclists going around the rotary on their way to the north and west suburbs.   Or a long line of parked cars on the bridge, whose owners are floating somewhere on the Concord River in a canoe or kayak.</p>

<div style="text-align:center">
<iframe width="425" height="350" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" src="http://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=great+meadow+wildlife+refuge,+sudbury&amp;aq=&amp;sll=41.814314,-71.921997&amp;sspn=2.028576,4.22699&amp;gl=us&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=great+meadow+wildlife+refuge,+sudbury&amp;hnear=&amp;t=k&amp;ll=42.475785,-71.336761&amp;spn=0.015684,0.033023&amp;output=embed"></iframe>


</div>


<p>After the chaos and excitement that was the <a href="http://www.yentran.org/blog/?p=310">Bruins Stanley Cup parade</a>, we decided to stop here for some relaxation and hopefully catch a heron or two.  "We&rsquo;re going to see 7,&ldquo; Kate said, wishfully.  It turned out that we only saw 4 herons.  But the ubiquitous red-winged blackbirds abounded in these marshes (according to Tanya, they should technically be called red-<em>shouldered</em> blackbirds).  Not advertised were the billions of mosquitoes who swarmed and attacked us at every available opportunity.  I lost count of how many mosquitoes I swatted, it couldn&rsquo;t have been fewer than about 1500.  Unfortunately herons don&rsquo;t prey on mosquitoes.  My tree swallow and bat friends, where were you?  Next time, I will have to bring a head net.</p>

